description.text:
Un spinner que j'ai crée pour ne pas avoir à utiliser les roulements à billes comme contre poids. Il en existe plusieurs de ce type, mais je voulais un spinner qui permettent à la fois une introduction facile des billes et qui les empêchent vraiment de sortir du fidget lors de la rotation. A moins de jeter le spinner par terre. Les billes resteront en place.
J'ai crée aussi le cap afin qu'il permette de voir le roulement à billes... parce que c'est cool de les voir tourner.
Le modele gris sur la photo a été imprimé en ABS et lissé à l'acétone. Attention, ce procédé peut déformer votre spinner et le déséquilibrer.

A spinner that I created for not having to use the ball bearings as counterweight. There are several of these, but I wanted a spinner that allow both an easy introduction of the marbles and that really prevent them from getting out of the fidget when rotated. Unless throw the spinner on the floor. Marbles will remain in place.
I also created this cap that it allows to see the ball bearing ... because it's cool to see them turn.
The gray one on the picture was printed in ABS and smoothed with acetone. Warning, this process can distort your spinner and unbalance it.

Notes:

Les roulements à billes peuvent être chers et difficiles à trouver.
Voici un spinner qui fonctionne avec des billes. Il est prévu pour un roulement à billes 608. Vous pouvez utiliser des billes classiques de 16 à 17,5 mm environ.

Pour insérer les billes, posez les du coté du chanfrein à l'emplacement prévu à cet effet. Une petite pression de la bille avec le pouce sur son emplacement suffira à l'enfoncer. Vous entendrez un "clic" qui signifiera qu'elle est bien enfoncée. Les billes tiennent tres bien dans leurs orifices, n'ayez pas peur de tourner votre spinner donc. Si toutefois les billes avaient tendances à partir, changer de calibre pour ces dernières ou rajouter un point de super glue à leur base.

Veillez à bien choisir les billes que vous mettrez dans le spinner, elles doivent avoir sensiblement le même poids.
Si vous voyez un trop gros déséquilibre lorsque vous faites tourner le spinner, tenez le verticalement entre vos doigts et laissez le bougez tout seul. Si il ne tourne pas du tout, c'est que le roulement est peut être désaxé. Si il tourne doucement et s'arrête, recommencez en mettant la bille qui se trouvait en bas après l'arrêt de la rotation de l'autre côté du spinner. Si le spinner se remet à tourner et que la même bille se retrouve à nouveau en bas; c'est qu'elle est trop lourde. Changez là et recommencez l'opération jusqu'à ce que vous obteniez une rotation stable.

Si le modèle apparait à la verticale dans le slicer, tournez le de maniere à ce qu'il soit à plat. Vous n'aurez pas besoin de raft ou de supports.

Avec le bon roulement et des billes bien équilibrées, ce spinner pourra tourner plus de 2 min.

Have fun.

Ball bearings can be expensive and hard to find.
Here is a spinner that works with marbles. It's designed for a ball bearing 608. You can use conventional marbles of about 15 to 16.5 mm.

To insert marbles, a small pressure of the marble with the thumb in its position will be enough to push it. You will hear a "click" that will mean it's pressed down. The marbles hold very well in their holes, do not be afraid to turn your spinner therefore. If, however, the balls had a tendency to go out, change their caliber for the latter or add a point of glue to their base.

Be sure to choose marbles you want to be in the spinner, they must have substantially the same weight.
If you see too much imbalance when you spin the spinner, hold it vertically between your fingers and let it move by itself. If it does not rotate at all, it is that the bearing is may be off-axis. If it turns gently and stops, start again by putting the marble which was at the bottom after the rotation of the other side of the spinner stopped. If the spinner starts to rotate again and the same marble is again at the bottom; Is that it is too heavy. Change it there and repeat the operation until you get a stable rotation.

If the model appears vertically in the slicer, turn it so that it is flat. Then you will not need raft or supports.

With good rolling and well balanced balls, this spinner can spin more than 2 min.

Have fun.

description.text:
This is a unique clock design. You can tell time with by looking at a series of twelve pegs on top of the clock, or with the LCD screen, if you need a more precise time. As time passes, a belt with a bump on it passes under the pegs (all happens hidden inside it) and rises them. One pass from left to right takes 12 hours, after which it takes another twelve hours to do it from right to left.
You can read time by looking at the pegs. If it's AM, then, if the second peg from the left is up, it's 2 AM. If it's PM, then it's the opposite : the second peg on the left means 10 PM. Take a look at my images, one explains it better.

To be build with a MakerBot in plastic. Time control works with an Arduino, linked to an external time keeping device (for more precision). The controller turns a 1 rotation per hour motor for 12 hours in one direction, then in the other direction for 12 hours. For even more precision, a full turn, free turning potentiometer can be connected to the output of the motor to calculate through the controller the speed of the motor, and then do any appropriate modification to speed.

Why try to improve a bad design to make it just a little bit less bad ? This thing is complex, bulky, heavy and despite the claims offer no practical advantage compared to a well thought and made (and here is the catch) hobbled gear and idler system. GT2 belt and pulleys are too bulky. Of course compared to archaic and poorly made extruders, it seemed to be a good idea years back !
Of course forget about flexible filament that offers the possibility to make some interesting stuff.

comments.text: Yes, it is big and heavy, but my printer's too. Advantage is of not using the hobbed gear which got filled with filament after some time. Contact area of gear and belt is uncomparable so I think, that the advantage can be seen at the first look. I had never such a quiet and reliable print until now right after printing and assembling the extruder, even without tuning the tension. If those spools were the only problem of this extruder, it would be a pity to abandone it. I tried this extruder because of few destroyed prints, when the filament stopped to flow into hotend. I even wanted to make a filament encoded monitor for this but then found this design and gave it a try too.
comments.author: MKSA

comments.text: I don't have any clogging of my hobbled gear and it can push filament with far more (40N) force than needed. A small lightweight extruder can be mounted on a small lightweight carriage to give far higher speed. 120mm/s even 180mm/s and takes any filament (flexible too). The Titan extruder is very good for people not having the tools, expertise to make their own.

description.text:
My Z endstop was getting bent down for some reason, and this caused numerous problems, both subtle and dramatic.

NOTE:
1) The height of this block is specific to my printer's bed height, nozzle length, and Zendstop screw adjustment. Which may not be - but should - be correct for any i3 mega.

comments.text:
I screwed the sensor on with two M3x4-8mm, and then another two M3x4-8mm to mount the whole unit.
The bolts screw into the plastic from both sides, so opposing M3x8mm should meet in the middle, anything shorter than 8mm will simply not extend as far into the plastic, but should be fine as long as they hold.

Would you make available your 3D design so that one customize it to fit? Or the dimensions you used to design the part?

comments.text:
I made it in Blender, as a mesh, unlike the solidworks file you were probably expecting there is nothing parametric about it, so it's going to be just as easy for you to edit the stl to make such trivial changes.
I am surprised it doesn't fit though. The height: not at all, that's dependent on the normal height of your bed and where you have your Z axis endstop fine tune adjustment screw set (the looong M3 bolt on the right side of the machine inside the gantry). But to hear that the width or depth of it doesn't fit is unexpected.
Just edit the stl to suit yours.

description.text:
These are the mounts I used to hold my Foam enclosure. The enclosure works well, and is easily made with 3 sheets of adams foam board from the Dollar store, cut with a sharp razor and hot glued together.

This enclosure is based on a similar design by Mike Kelly​. His Acrylic enclosure is bombproof, and available as a kit from www.printed Solid.com. https://printedsolid.com/collections/accessories-and-upgrades/products/robo-3d-safety-enclosure-kit If you cant work with acrylic then this foam enclosure may be a good option for you.

The Case clip is designed to press up on the Robo3D cover. It should be a slight press fit. I use a M3 x 16-20mm bolt with a thumb nut to act as the clamp.

The Mount Hole Reinforcing part is hot glued on TOP of the enclosure halves. The tang should fit nicely in the notches of the foam. This piece prevents wear from repeated use.

Here is a link to 2 versions of the enclosure. One is Flat on all sides, one has 'tabs' to interlock together. Helps keep it square, but takes longer to cut. Anything dashed is optional cuts. (Windows, mount notches)
https://culpandtanner-my.sharepoint.com/personal/jleonard_culpandtanner_com/_layouts/15/guestaccess.aspx?folderid=0aa1d17b07bb04ed9972a7b67f3101071&authkey=AcAkolExGTCMoJL160wLgHs&e=8d5fdea29b9449b78521778f789c4ea4

Here is the Acrylic I used for the windows. The openings on the templates are 6" x 8.375", so I cut the sheet to 9.5" and then split in half to have (2) 7" X 9.5" windows. http://www.osh.com/Osh-Categories/Optix-Acrylic-Sheet%2C-14-Inch-L-x-11-Inch-W-x-0-093-Inch-T%2C-Clear/p/6453153

Here are the Thumb nuts I used for the mount clamps. A quarter turn is all that is necessary, and will not crush the foam. You may want to open up the top hole so the threads don't bind then tightening/loosening the nut. https://www.amainhobbies.com/search?s=exotek+m3

description.text:
NOTE: I have fixed the customizer since I uploaded it.  
Lock Bridges have been a growing worldwide trend for the last decade. Those in love go to the bridges together with a lock and attach it to the bridge to signify their bond. Typically couples write their information with black sharpies onto the locks. I have seen the lock bridge in Paris and my girlfriend and I have a lock on the Phipps bridge in Pittsburgh.  
One sad thing you notice when you walk past one of these lock bridges is that the sharpie has warn off most of the locks. A proud few have engraved locks and avoid these troubles. With Valentines Day approaching and lost for ideas of what parametric object to make. I decided to make a customizable lock, so that anyone with a 3D printer could have a customized lock that would withstand the outdoors better.  
Due to my lack of experience with making locks, I made the lock design be unopenable once closed the first time (when you put the lock on the bridge, you can't open it, which is actually the point of it so it worked out well). I have not gotten to test the lock because I don't have a 3D printer, but I believe it should be functional and if not, would just require minor tweaking. I didn't appreciate the pain of constructing a lock until now.

description.text: Turn your worthless PLA scrap into unique works of art :)

You will need - An oven
Baking tray
Aluminium foil
Scrap bits of PLA and any failed prints
Beer - (to help with artistic inspiration) Lay the Aluminium foil on the tray and place your largest scrap parts onto it, don't space them too much apart as they will produce a smaller pool of plastic than you would think. Optionally use some filament to make a round or shaped outer ring to keep all the plastic in if you want a nice shape. (PLA Pizza Anyone?) Pop it in the oven, heat up to 210 Degrees C for about 15 mins Then scatter on the smaller parts and heat at whatever temperature you like - 160 Degrees will make things go soft and still keep some shape of what they once were. It's also quite interesting to throw in some ABS parts as that shrink, distort and go soft creating a more 3D sculpture. Keep an eye on the cooking, and remove when you have the desired effect, leave to cool for a few mins and then you can trim the foil and PLA to size (wear oven gloves, if you handle it HOT!) you can form it around shapes, bottles, plates etc. or cut out butterfly shapes if you like. You should have about 5 mins cutting time, or pop it back in the oven to make it soft again. I hope some of you try it, it's good fun and you may just make a masterpiece. I'm calling my two first attempts - Raspberry Pizza Pi (As a tribute to the Great RPi case by HansH) - http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:16104 ) and 'April-12' as this was all my failed plastic in April of this year.

description.text:
Continuation of my previous project, see http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2122538 for reference.

This is a work in progress! I didn't print out a test assembly of this just yet, you can try to print this as is but i can't guarantee that all parts will fit (although i'm confident they should)

This gearbox fits on top of a NEMA 17 standard motor and sides of the reducer sit flush with the motor. This gearbox has a 40:1 ratio and double 608z bearings to support the output ring so it can actually deliver torque at the output without unwanted movements inside the assembly. In a 2 bearing version it's ONLY 26mm thick, and in the single bearing version it's going to be only 19mm.
I have yet to see a greater reduction in a smaller package which can be readily mounted on a NEMA 17 motor (such reducers most likely exist, but i haven't seen them)

Anyways, this is WIP, and i'll update it as the project goes along.

title: Knurled Coupling for Z-Axis - fully parametrized

description.text: I am using stepper motors with 4mm shaft diameter, but most of the available z-axis couplings assume motors with a 5mm shaft. And since I also like to use the z-axis couplings as "knobs" to fine-tune manually the level and skewness of the z-coordinate, I like them to have a good tactile grip. Since I couldn't find exactly what I had in mind among the many z-couplings available on Thingiverse, I ended up with my own knurled design. The SCAD file is fully parametrized. Not just the diameters of the motor shaft and the threaded rod can be adjusted, but also the outer profile, the height, the number of grub screw holes and even the number of knurls are parametrized. Ready-to-print STL files are provided stepper motor shafts with a diameter of 4mm or 5mm, and for M8 (Mendel) and M5 (i3) threaded rods. Update 2015-10-05: I have now added three new STL files which have three nut traps on each side: KnurledCoupling_5mm_4mm_3g.stl, KnurledCoupling_5mm_5mm_3g.stl and KnurledCoupling_8mm_4mm_3g.stl. These couplings, produced with the original SCAD file, allow much more precise alignemnt of the motor axis with the threaded rod, by adjusting the three grub screws individually. So, if you got excessive wobbling of the Z-axis, use these versions with three grub screws and adjust them carefully until the threaded Z-rod rotates without any lateral movement.

I printed my z-couplings using ABS with 0.25mm layers and 0.56mm extrusion width.  
The holes are all coded very tightly.  I prefer them to be a bit too small and the use the drill to get the holes to have the right diameter and to be perfect cylindrical.  
The motor shaft and the threaded rod are fixated to the coupling by means of M3 grub screws which are held by corresponding screw nuts inserted into the provided nut cavities.  These cavities are also rather tight, so sometimes I need to push the nuts into the cavities using my soldering iron.  In any case, I prefer the nuts to stick firmly to the coupling, so that they don't fall out.

description.text:
Increasing regulations protecting the endangered wild unicorn population and tighter restrictions on the unicorn ivory trade have made it all but impossible to legally obtain legitimate unicorn horns.

Instead of turning to a counterfeit specimen or a black-market horn from a poacher, print your own lifelike replica using these models!

These horns were painstakingly recreated using five of the major unicorn subspecies as references. No unicorns were harmed in the creation of these models.

Read more about the creation of these on my blog: https://roadtopolymathy.wordpress.com/2017/05/15/magic-materials-monday-unicorn-horns/

Notes:

Slic3r's spiral vase setting was used for the illuminated horns in the photo. Pictured materials are White ABS and Translucent Green PETG, both by Inland. The white ABS horn is lit with a single 8mm diffused blue LED, and the green PETG horn is lit with a 5mm white LED.

Be careful when printing these without infill- too high of a temperature will cause ugly distortions toward the horn's tip as the layers get less time to cool.

Robots are cool, right? So a parametric model of a robot head where a user can adjust the size of various facial features must be super fly. The code allows for the adjustment of 5 attributes: antenna height, antenna ball radius, eye diameter, the spacing between the eyes, and the height of the mouth. I think that if animated, these attributes when manipulated programmatically, could resemble dialog, facial expressions, or even emotional states.

Included is the OpenSCAD source code, where you can manipulate the the parameters at the top of the file to change how the robot head is rendered. There is no error checking for proper values, so watch out if you put in some crazy values.
